Blog Post #3 – First Milestone: City Generation 

The first milestone of our police chase game focused on building the game world and making the two main cars appear correctly inside it. Even though this was only the 
beginning of the project, it ended up being one of the more challenging parts because the entire gameplay depends on the city layout working properly. 

At the start, we imported different assets and materials from the asset store to help us create the environment faster. However, once we started generating the city, 
we quickly realized that things were not working the way we expected. Roads, buildings, and intersections were often placed randomly, which made the city look messy 
and unrealistic. Some roads would suddenly end, others would overlap, and many areas simply did not make sense for driving gameplay. 

One of our biggest problems was making sure the roads were logical. Since this is a police chase game, players need to be able to drive naturally through the city. We 
had to make sure intersections and cross traffic lines looked normal and connected correctly. Otherwise, the map became confusing and difficult to play on. 

Another issue was making sure every house or building was connected to at least one road. In early versions of the city generation, some houses were isolated with no 
proper access, which made the environment feel broken. We spent a lot of time adjusting the generation system so the city would feel more realistic and organized. 

We also wanted to avoid making the game too easy. At one point, some roads stretched directly from one side of the map to the other without obstacles or meaningful 
turns. This removed the challenge from the police chase because players could simply drive in a straight line until reaching the escape road. To fix this, we 
redesigned the road generation so the map encouraged turning, escaping, and decision-making during gameplay. (we can add some code snipperts here) 

Another important thing we had to consider was route connectivity. We needed to make sure there was always a possible route through the city and that not every road 
ended in a dead end. If too many roads were blocked or disconnected, the gameplay became frustrating instead of fun. Finding the right balance between open roads and 
dead ends took a lot of testing and experimentation. 

Alongside the city generation, we also worked on spawning the two vehicles into the game. One car represented the police player, while the other represented the 
escaping player. We had to make sure the cars spawned in valid positions on the roads and did not collide with buildings or objects when the game started. 

Even though this milestone was mostly focused on the environment, it taught us a lot about procedural generation and level design. It was much harder than we 
originally expected because every small issue with the roads affected the gameplay directly. 

By the end of the milestone, we finally had a city that felt playable and supported the kind of police chase experience we wanted to create. Seeing both cars driving 
through a properly connected city was the moment when the project truly started to feel like a real game. 
